<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
  <chapter xml:id="ch-meta-intro" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Metaprogramming: Introduction</title>

    <p>
      One of the most intriguing things about R is its capability for
      metaprogramming: the ability of code to inspect and modify other code.
      This is most commonly seen in R as non-standard evaluation (NSE): the
      ability of functions to quote arguments rather than evaluating them.
    </p>

    <p>
      The following chapters explain the metaprogramming capabilities of R:
    </p>

    <p><ol>
      <li><p>
        <xref ref="ch-meta-big-picture"/> gives you a big picture of
        metaprogramming. It introduces important vocabulary, gives a broad
        overview of the main ideas, and introduces a few simpler tools.
      </p></li>
      <li><p>
        <xref ref="ch-expressions"/> dives into the details of expressions:
        the data structures that represent code.
      </p></li>
      <li><p>
        <xref ref="ch-quasiquotation"/> teaches you about quasiquotation, which
        allows you to create code that mixes user-supplied code and developer
        code.
      </p></li>
      <li><p>
        <xref ref="ch-evaluation"/> shows how to take an expression and evaluate
        it in a custom environment.
      </p></li>
      <li><p>
        <xref ref="ch-translation"/> ties the previous four chapters together
        by showing how you might use metaprogramming to translate R code into
        another language.
      </p></li>
    </ol></p>

  </chapter>
